es. New York City Politics focuses on the impact of these three forces on the governance of New York City’s political system including the need to promote democratic accountability, service delivery equity, as well as the maintenance of civil harmony. This second edition updates the discussion with examples from the Bloomberg and de Blasio administrations as well as current public policy issues including infrastructure, housing and homelessness, land use regulations, and education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  a911.  aBrooklyn.  aDavid Dinkins.  aEmpire State.  aJane Jacobs.  aJohn Lindsay.  aLaGuardia.  aMTA.  aManhattan.  aMayor Bloomberg.  aMayor de Blasio.  aNew York City.  aNew York.  aPenn Station.  aQueens.  aRobert Moses.  aRudy Guiliani.  aStaten Island.  aThe Bronx.  aWolrd Trade Center.  acity council.  acity.  adevelopment.  agentrification.  agovernment.  ahousing.  amayor.  amunicipal bureaucracy.  apolitics.  apublic policy.  arent control.  astate.  asubway.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081358669440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813586694423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813586694.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK